      <hedline>
        <hl1>Prosperity and Poverty</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by Stephen Kagann, chief economist to Gov George Pataki, interprets data on low-wage jobs and poverty rates in New York</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Low-Wage Jobs Leading Gains in Employment'' (front page, Oct. 1):</p>
        <p>''Real wages'' are derived by dividing the wages by the Consumer Price Index. It is widely accepted that the index has overestimated inflation. If the index is too high, derived real wages are too low.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Low-Wage Jobs Leading Gains in Employment'' (front page, Oct. 1):</p>
        <p>''Real wages'' are derived by dividing the wages by the Consumer Price Index. It is widely accepted that the index has overestimated inflation. If the index is too high, derived real wages are too low.</p>
        <p>In 1996, the Boskin Commission estimated that the index was overstating inflation by more than 1 percent per year. With a more accurate measure of inflation, the real earnings of the cited groups did not fall at all -- real earnings rose.</p>
        <p>Census data show that the poverty rate in New York declined from a peak of 17 percent in 1994 to 14.1 percent in 1999. Moreover, New York was one of only four states to experience both a significant decline in poverty and a rise in real income.</p>
        <p>As a matter of statistics or common sense, prosperity does not breed poverty.</p>
        <p>STEPHEN KAGANN  New York, Oct. 3, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is chief economist to Gov. George E. Pataki.</p>
      </block>
